The 12–15 Universal Relationship Types

Across knowledge graphs, linguistics, and logic, most information reduces to a small set of relationships.

These are the core ones.

⸻

1 — Identity

A IS B

Example:

water IS H₂O


⸻

2 — Classification

A TYPE_OF B

Example:

whale TYPE_OF mammal


⸻

3 — Part–Whole

A PART_OF B

Example:

wheel PART_OF car


⸻

4 — Causation

A CAUSES B

Example:

rain CAUSES flooding


⸻

5 — Influence

A INCREASES B
A DECREASES B

Example:

stress INCREASES cortisol


⸻

6 — Dependency

A DEPENDS_ON B

Example:

plant_growth DEPENDS_ON sunlight


⸻

7 — Constraint

A LIMITS B

Example:

resources LIMIT population


⸻

8 — Sequence

A PRECEDES B

Example:

seed PRECEDES plant


⸻

9 — Feedback

A AMPLIFIES B
A STABILIZES B

Example:

predators STABILIZE ecosystem


⸻

10 — Correlation

A CORRELATES_WITH B

Example:

education CORRELATES_WITH income


⸻

11 — Transformation

A BECOMES B

Example:

water BECOMES ice


⸻

12 — Equivalence

A EQUIVALENT_TO B

Example:

1/2 EQUIVALENT_TO 0.5


⸻

13 — Possession

A HAS B

Example:

bird HAS wings


⸻

14 — Location / containment

A IN B

Example:

fish IN water


⸻

15 — Agency

A ACTS_ON B

Example:

doctor ACTS_ON patient


⸻

Why these matter

Nearly all reasoning systems reduce to combinations of these.

Example:

speculation INCREASES volatility
volatility INCREASES instability

This becomes a reasoning chain.

